1
00:00:00,700 --> 00:00:01,700
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,700 --> 00:00:03,420
A Short History

3
00:00:03,420 --> 00:00:13,190
Back in England's oldest times, people lived
in big groups called tribes.

4
00:00:13,190 --> 00:00:19,030
They were farmers - they grew their food,
and kept animals for meat and eggs.

5
00:00:19,030 --> 00:00:26,560
They lived in villages, in wooden or mud houses,
and there was often fighting between the different

6
00:00:26,560 --> 00:00:28,730
tribes.

7
00:00:28,730 --> 00:00:31,980
Life was simple but dangerous.

8
00:00:31,980 --> 00:00:41,160
Then in AD 43, forty thousand Roman soldiers
invaded England from the area of Europe that

9
00:00:41,160 --> 00:00:44,150
is now Italy.

10
00:00:44,150 --> 00:00:49,730
The Roman army was very well-organized and
had good weapons.

11
00:00:49,730 --> 00:00:56,200
The soldiers built a wall around themselves
every night so they were safe.

12
00:00:56,200 --> 00:01:02,420
They moved across the country, fighting and
winning battles against the different tribes,

13
00:01:02,420 --> 00:01:07,200
and after four years they controlled the south
of England.

14
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:13,039
The Romans had to fight for many years before
they controlled all of England.

15
00:01:13,039 --> 00:01:20,139
They made many changes in the country, such
as building towns and cities, and good roads.

16
00:01:20,139 --> 00:01:26,229
They brought a new language to England - Latin
- and made laws, so people knew what they

17
00:01:26,229 --> 00:01:29,560
could and could not do.

18
00:01:29,560 --> 00:01:35,150
The religion of Christianity came to England
in Roman times too.

19
00:01:35,150 --> 00:01:41,119
The Romans never took control of Scotland,
which is north of England, and Scottish tribes

20
00:01:41,119 --> 00:01:46,149
came to fight against them in the north of
England again and again.

21
00:01:46,149 --> 00:01:52,439
Because of this, in the second century AD,
the Romans built a wall to stop the Scottish

22
00:01:52,439 --> 00:01:54,959
tribes coming to England.

23
00:01:54,959 --> 00:02:00,710
This wall between England and Scotland was
one hundred and twenty kilometers long, and

24
00:02:00,710 --> 00:02:04,159
was called Hadrian's Wall.

25
00:02:04,159 --> 00:02:09,340
For English people in towns and cities, life
in Roman times was good.

26
00:02:09,340 --> 00:02:16,849
Towns now had clean water and sewers (pipes
taking away dirty water), and there were strong

27
00:02:16,849 --> 00:02:21,849
walls around them, so people felt safe.

28
00:02:21,849 --> 00:02:29,329
People came to the towns to buy and sell things,
and food became more interesting and enjoyable.

29
00:02:29,329 --> 00:02:35,260
To relax, people could go to special bath
houses, where they met their friends, kept

30
00:02:35,260 --> 00:02:38,189
clean and exercised.

31
00:02:38,189 --> 00:02:43,720
But after AD 250, Roman soldiers began to
leave England.

32
00:02:43,720 --> 00:02:49,579
They had to fight in other parts of the world,
and it was too expensive and difficult for

33
00:02:49,579 --> 00:02:53,140
them to keep England safe.

34
00:02:53,140 --> 00:02:59,230
By AD 411, all the Roman soldiers had left
England.

35
00:02:59,230 --> 00:03:06,629
Then the Anglo-Saxons, from Germany, the Netherlands
and Denmark, began to arrive.

36
00:03:06,629 --> 00:03:12,519
The Anglo-Saxons had come to England several
times before, but the Romans had always defeated

37
00:03:12,519 --> 00:03:13,659
them.

38
00:03:13,659 --> 00:03:20,420
Now, with the Romans gone, the English could
not win battles against the Anglo-Saxons,

39
00:03:20,420 --> 00:03:24,459
and many Anglo-Saxons came to live in England.

40
00:03:24,459 --> 00:03:30,459
The Anglo-Saxons did not like the Romans'
towns, so they did not use them, and the towns

41
00:03:30,459 --> 00:03:32,920
stayed empty.

42
00:03:32,920 --> 00:03:39,200
The AngloSaxons built their own villages near
rivers or the sea and made wooden houses.

43
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:45,330
In their villages, they grew crops - plants
they could use for food.

44
00:03:45,330 --> 00:03:51,640
They also kept pigs, sheep and cows, and caught
fish and other animals.

45
00:03:51,640 --> 00:04:00,670
By AD 600 in England, the AngloSaxons had
made seven kingdoms - different parts of the

46
00:04:00,670 --> 00:04:04,900
country, each controlled by its own king.

47
00:04:04,900 --> 00:04:12,680
The four main kingdoms were Northumbria, Mercia,
East Anglia and Wessex.

48
00:04:12,680 --> 00:04:18,780
The three minor kingdoms were Essex, Kent
and Sussex.

49
00:04:18,780 --> 00:04:26,610
In each of these kingdoms, the king had nobles
- important men who fought for him.

50
00:04:26,610 --> 00:04:31,150
The other people in the kingdom were either
peasants or slaves.

51
00:04:31,150 --> 00:04:37,470
Peasants were poor people who had some land,
but had to give money to the nobles.

52
00:04:37,470 --> 00:04:44,050
Slaves had nothing and had to work for other
people for no money at all.

53
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:48,610
People bought and sold slaves like animals.

54
00:04:48,610 --> 00:04:57,610
The Anglo-Saxons stayed in England, but in
AD 793 a new group of people invaded the country.

55
00:04:57,610 --> 00:05:04,670
The Vikings, from Norway, Sweden and Denmark,
wanted good farming land.

56
00:05:04,670 --> 00:05:10,610
They came to England in strong wooden ships,
and soon they took control of many parts of

57
00:05:10,610 --> 00:05:12,510
the country.

58
00:05:12,510 --> 00:05:18,990
But the Anglo-Saxon king of Wessex, Alfred
the Great, won a big battle against the Vikings.

59
00:05:18,990 --> 00:05:26,170
After this, part of England, called Danelaw,
was given to the Vikings, but the Vikings

60
00:05:26,170 --> 00:05:30,810
had to promise not to invade other parts of
the country.

61
00:05:30,810 --> 00:05:36,930
After Alfred the Great died, the Viking and
Anglo-Saxon parts of England came together,

62
00:05:36,930 --> 00:05:41,980
and England was now ruled as one country with
one king.

63
00:05:41,980 --> 00:05:48,330
The Vikings and the Anglo-Saxons continued
to fight a lot, and for a while England had

64
00:05:48,330 --> 00:05:57,110
Viking kings, but by 1042, the Anglo-Saxon
King Edward ruled England.

65
00:05:57,110 --> 00:06:02,860
With Edward as the king, London became the
most important city in England.

66
00:06:02,860 --> 00:06:09,210
Edward had many nobles, and he let them become
very powerful.

67
00:06:09,210 --> 00:06:16,240
He had no children, so when he died, one of
his nobles, Harold, became the king.

68
00:06:16,240 --> 00:06:21,920
But Edward's cousin William, a Norman (from
the north of France), believed that he should

69
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:23,910
be the king of England.

70
00:06:23,910 --> 00:06:30,900
In October 1066, William brought a big Norman
army from France to England.

71
00:06:30,900 --> 00:06:37,030
The Normans fought against Harold and his
soldiers at the Battle of Hastings.

72
00:06:37,030 --> 00:06:44,670
Harold was killed, and William the Conqueror,
as he was called, became the king of England.

73
00:06:44,670 --> 00:06:49,100
William the Conqueror made many important
changes in England.

74
00:06:49,100 --> 00:06:51,800
A lot of castles were built.

75
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:57,610
One of these was the Tower of London, which
you can visit today.

76
00:06:57,610 --> 00:07:02,140
William the Conqueror brought the feudal system
to England.

77
00:07:02,140 --> 00:07:07,280
In the feudal system, the richest and most
important person was the king.

78
00:07:07,280 --> 00:07:14,490
Below the king were the nobles, then the knights
and then the serfs, who were the poorest people

79
00:07:14,490 --> 00:07:16,970
in the land.

80
00:07:16,970 --> 00:07:23,680
The king owned everything in the country,
but he gave a castle and land to his nobles,

81
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:25,900
and they paid him money.

82
00:07:25,900 --> 00:07:33,900
The nobles gave land to the knights, who had
to fight battles for the nobles and the king.

83
00:07:33,900 --> 00:07:38,840
The knights gave some land to the serfs, who
had to work for the knights and give them

84
00:07:38,840 --> 00:07:42,180
food from the land.

85
00:07:42,180 --> 00:07:47,150
William the Conqueror wanted to know exactly
what he had in England.

86
00:07:47,150 --> 00:07:53,810
He sent people all around the country, asking
many questions, and they made a big book called

87
00:07:53,810 --> 00:07:56,500
the Domesday Book.

88
00:07:56,500 --> 00:08:03,240
The book showed how much farming land there
was in England and how many animals.

89
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:08,000
We know a lot about life in Norman England
because of the Domesday Book.

90
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:13,710
The time from William the Conqueror's rule
until the fifteenth century in England is

91
00:08:13,710 --> 00:08:16,890
often called the Middle Ages.

92
00:08:16,890 --> 00:08:20,590
In the Middle Ages, most people lived in villages.

93
00:08:20,590 --> 00:08:27,950
The people of the village had to work for
the nobles, and give them crops and animals.

94
00:08:27,950 --> 00:08:34,531
The nobles lived very well, in big houses
and with expensive food, but most people were

95
00:08:34,531 --> 00:08:38,090
very poor.

96
00:08:38,090 --> 00:08:43,190
Religion was very important in the Middle
Ages, and the Catholic Church became very

97
00:08:43,190 --> 00:08:44,270
powerful.

98
00:08:44,270 --> 00:08:53,500
From 1095 to 1291, soldiers went to other
countries to fight religious battles.

99
00:08:53,500 --> 00:08:58,570
There was more fighting in the fourteenth
and fifteenth centuries, as France and England

100
00:08:58,570 --> 00:09:05,690
fought the Hundred Years War, hoping to win
land from each other.

101
00:09:05,690 --> 00:09:10,560
Many of the battles of the Hundred Years War
were fought by knights.

102
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:16,330
As well as fighting battles for nobles and
for the king, knights also fought as a sport

103
00:09:16,330 --> 00:09:19,810
in competitions called jousting tournaments.

104
00:09:19,810 --> 00:09:25,740
Young men who wanted to become knights had
to spend many years learning all the things

105
00:09:25,740 --> 00:09:28,630
that a knight could do.

106
00:09:28,630 --> 00:09:35,700
In 1348, a terrible illness called The Black
Death came to England.

107
00:09:35,700 --> 00:09:42,130
Only about four million people lived in England
at that time, but in two years, nearly one-and-a-half

108
00:09:42,130 --> 00:09:45,680
million of them died.

109
00:09:45,680 --> 00:09:53,480
From 1455-1485, there were terrible battles
between people who wanted the kings of the

110
00:09:53,480 --> 00:09:59,080
country to be from different families, and
many more people died.

111
00:09:59,080 --> 00:10:10,340
Finally, in 1485, Henry Tudor became the first
Tudor king of England, King Henry the Seventh.

112
00:10:10,340 --> 00:10:15,640
Some of the Tudor kings and queens are now
very famous in England's history.

113
00:10:15,640 --> 00:10:23,240
Henry the Eighth, who became the king in 1509,
lived some of the time at the Tower of London,

114
00:10:23,240 --> 00:10:29,860
but he had other beautiful palaces in and
around London, including the Palace of Westminster

115
00:10:29,860 --> 00:10:32,420
and Hampton Court.

116
00:10:32,420 --> 00:10:35,640
He and the people around him lived very well.

117
00:10:35,640 --> 00:10:41,930
They wore the best clothes and ate wonderful
food, and at the palaces there was always

118
00:10:41,930 --> 00:10:46,510
dancing, sport, poetry and music.

119
00:10:46,510 --> 00:10:51,610
Henry enjoyed life, and he drank and ate too
much.

120
00:10:51,610 --> 00:10:57,420
When he became the king, he was a sporty,
good-looking young man, but later he became

121
00:10:57,420 --> 00:11:00,710
so fat he could not walk!

122
00:11:00,710 --> 00:11:07,000
England was a Catholic country, but Henry
the Eighth wanted England to leave the Catholic

123
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,170
Church, so he started a new church.

124
00:11:10,170 --> 00:11:17,350
It was a Protestant church (a Christian church,
but for people who believe in a different

125
00:11:17,350 --> 00:11:23,990
kind of Christianity) called the Church of
England, and he controlled it.

126
00:11:23,990 --> 00:11:30,120
Anyone who disagreed with the new church was
executed - killed for their crime.

127
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:35,220
When Henry the Eighth was ruling England,
more than seventy thousand people were killed

128
00:11:35,220 --> 00:11:40,890
because of crimes, or because they disagreed
with the king about religion or other important

129
00:11:40,890 --> 00:11:43,300
things.

130
00:11:43,300 --> 00:11:48,810
Six years after Henry the Eighth died, his
oldest daughter Mary - the daughter he had

131
00:11:48,810 --> 00:11:54,990
with his first wife, Catherine of Aragon - became
Queen Mary the First of England.

132
00:11:54,990 --> 00:12:01,030
She was a Catholic and wanted England to be
a Catholic country again, but many people

133
00:12:01,030 --> 00:12:05,510
had left the Catholic Church and had become
Protestants.

134
00:12:05,510 --> 00:12:11,790
Mary executed hundreds of Protestants who
refused to become Catholic again.

135
00:12:11,790 --> 00:12:18,610
But in 1558, Mary died, and her half-sister
Elizabeth - the daughter Henry had with his

136
00:12:18,610 --> 00:12:22,610
second wife Anne Boleyn - became the queen.

137
00:12:22,610 --> 00:12:27,800
Queen Elizabeth the First was a Protestant,
but she did not make Catholics follow her

138
00:12:27,800 --> 00:12:33,930
religion, and she soon became one of the best
loved of England's kings and queens.

139
00:12:33,930 --> 00:12:39,040
The second half of the sixteenth century,
which was known as the Elizabethan period,

140
00:12:39,040 --> 00:12:43,250
was a very important time for English literature.

141
00:12:43,250 --> 00:12:48,589
Many people liked to go to the theatre, and
William Shakespeare wrote a lot of plays and

142
00:12:48,589 --> 00:12:50,840
poetry at this time.

143
00:12:50,840 --> 00:12:55,550
Ships also began to travel to other parts
of the world.

144
00:12:55,550 --> 00:13:02,080
Sir Walter Raleigh sailed to America, and
Sir Francis Drake became the first Englishman

145
00:13:02,080 --> 00:13:05,860
to sail around the world.

146
00:13:05,860 --> 00:13:11,660
But life in England was also very difficult
for many people in the Elizabethan period.

147
00:13:11,660 --> 00:13:17,290
There was less work in farming now, and a
lot of people were very poor.

148
00:13:17,290 --> 00:13:23,030
There was a lot of crime, but no police, and
when people were caught for crimes, they were

149
00:13:23,030 --> 00:13:24,910
often executed.

150
00:13:24,910 --> 00:13:32,550
Alter Queen Elizabeth the First died in 1603,
kings and queens called the Stuarts came to

151
00:13:32,550 --> 00:13:34,990
power in England.

152
00:13:34,990 --> 00:13:41,970
The Stuarts were from Scotland, and for the
first time, they ruled both England and Scotland.

153
00:13:41,970 --> 00:13:47,410
The second of the Stuart kings was Charles
the First.

154
00:13:47,410 --> 00:13:53,170
He argued with Parliament because he spent
a lot of money fighting wars in Europe, and

155
00:13:53,170 --> 00:13:58,130
in 1642, he started a civil war.

156
00:13:58,130 --> 00:14:05,300
For seven years, the King's men and Parliaments
men fought against each other, and thousands

157
00:14:05,300 --> 00:14:06,529
died.

158
00:14:06,529 --> 00:14:13,830
But with Oliver Cromwell as leader, Parliaments
army became very strong and fought very well,

159
00:14:13,830 --> 00:14:18,250
and in 1649, they won the war.

160
00:14:18,250 --> 00:14:25,500
Charles the First was executed, and for eleven
years England had no king or queen.

161
00:14:25,500 --> 00:14:30,980
The country was ruled by Cromwell and Parliament.

162
00:14:30,980 --> 00:14:37,610
Cromwell was a Puritan - a Protestant who
believed in a simple, hard-working life - and

163
00:14:37,610 --> 00:14:44,650
when he ruled, there was no sport or dancing
in England, and theatres were closed.

164
00:14:44,650 --> 00:14:50,460
When Cromwell died, England was ready to have
a king again, and the Stuarts came to power

165
00:14:50,460 --> 00:14:51,890
once more.

166
00:14:51,890 --> 00:14:58,529
There were some difficult times for England
in the second half of the seventeenth century.

167
00:14:58,529 --> 00:15:05,020
In 1665, another terrible illness came to
London and killed nearly seventy thousand

168
00:15:05,020 --> 00:15:12,740
people, and a year later, large parts of London
were burnt down in the Great Fire of London.

169
00:15:12,740 --> 00:15:16,990
There were many other changes at this time
too.

170
00:15:16,990 --> 00:15:23,420
England now traded - bought and sold things
- with many other countries, so English people

171
00:15:23,420 --> 00:15:31,250
could get different foods like tomatoes, chocolate,
coffee and tea for the first time.

172
00:15:31,250 --> 00:15:36,430
People continued to work on the land, but
now there were other jobs, in cloth-making

173
00:15:36,430 --> 00:15:42,230
or glass-making, and in the coal or iron industries.

174
00:15:42,230 --> 00:15:48,370
London was rebuilt with wider roads and many
beautiful new buildings, and scientists like

175
00:15:48,370 --> 00:15:55,240
Sir Isaac Newton began to do important work
and learn many interesting things.

176
00:15:55,240 --> 00:15:58,850
England started its first colonies too.

177
00:15:58,850 --> 00:16:04,430
These were other parts of the world, like
America, which were ruled by England.

178
00:16:04,430 --> 00:16:09,589
For the first time in the seventeenth century,
people from England went to live and work

179
00:16:09,589 --> 00:16:11,190
in these places.

180
00:16:11,190 --> 00:16:17,600
There was one more important change as England
entered the eighteenth century.

181
00:16:17,600 --> 00:16:24,390
In 1707, the Act of Union brought England,
Wales and Scotland together with one parliament

182
00:16:24,390 --> 00:16:26,730
as Great Britain.

183
00:16:26,730 --> 00:16:32,270
The eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries
were called the Georgian period because Britain's

184
00:16:32,270 --> 00:16:36,510
kings were George the First, Second, Third
and Fourth.

185
00:16:36,510 --> 00:16:43,170
But during this time, kings became much less
powerful, and Parliament really began to rule

186
00:16:43,170 --> 00:16:44,589
the country.

187
00:16:44,589 --> 00:16:51,089
An industrial revolution began in Britain
too: machines were built, and they were used

188
00:16:51,089 --> 00:16:54,050
in many different industries.

189
00:16:54,050 --> 00:17:00,700
People could now make many things very quickly,
and because of this towns began to grow.

190
00:17:00,700 --> 00:17:07,620
In 1783, Britain lost the American War of
Independence, so America was no longer ruled

191
00:17:07,620 --> 00:17:11,579
by Britain and became independent.

192
00:17:11,579 --> 00:17:18,350
Britain did not have its old American colonies
anymore, but it now found new ones.

193
00:17:18,350 --> 00:17:24,119
In that same year, France gave its colonies
in Canada to Britain, and by the end of the

194
00:17:24,119 --> 00:17:29,929
eighteenth century, Britain had won many battles
in India, which soon became an important part

195
00:17:29,929 --> 00:17:32,489
of the British Empire.

196
00:17:32,489 --> 00:17:39,110
This was a great time for exploration: travelling
to different places to find new things.

197
00:17:39,110 --> 00:17:44,919
The famous sailor Captain Cook visited many
new lands and was the first European to go

198
00:17:44,919 --> 00:17:48,600
to Australia and New Zealand.

199
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:55,710
In 1801, Ireland and Britain came together
as the United Kingdom (UK) with one parliament.

200
00:17:55,710 --> 00:18:01,830
(Today, Northern Ireland is the only part
of Ireland which belongs to the UK.)

201
00:18:01,830 --> 00:18:11,720
The ruler of this new UK, from 1837 until
1901, was Queen Victoria.

202
00:18:11,720 --> 00:18:17,110
Victoria ruled for longer than any other English
or British king or queen, and she was much

203
00:18:17,110 --> 00:18:20,990
loved by many of her people.

204
00:18:20,990 --> 00:18:23,470
In the Victorian period, the British

205
00:18:23,470 --> 00:18:30,519
Empire became bigger and more important, and
the industrial revolution continued.

206
00:18:30,519 --> 00:18:36,610
The country was growing, but at first this
made life difficult for many people.

207
00:18:36,610 --> 00:18:41,929
More and more factories were built in the
UK, and factory work was very hard and very

208
00:18:41,929 --> 00:18:43,629
dangerous.

209
00:18:43,629 --> 00:18:49,110
Towns got bigger and bigger, but people put
their rubbish and dirty water in the streets,

210
00:18:49,110 --> 00:18:52,149
so there was a lot of illness.

211
00:18:52,149 --> 00:18:56,679
But soon important new changes started to
happen.

212
00:18:56,679 --> 00:19:05,940
Towns became cleaner, and in 1880, all children
aged 5-10 began to go to school.

213
00:19:05,940 --> 00:19:11,590
People had electric lights and telephones
for the first time, and because the railways

214
00:19:11,590 --> 00:19:15,320
grew, they could now travel around the country
easily.

215
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:42,799
By 1901, when Queen Victoria died, the modern
United Kingdom was arriving.

216
00:19:42,799 --> 00:19:44,679
