For two weeks around the end of Traditionally,
when people June, England becomes tennis-mad!

899
01:20:10,690 --> 01:20:13,820
This is the time of the Wimbledon they eat
strawberries and cream.

900
01:20:13,820 --> 01:20:18,330
Championships, the most famous tennis tournament
in the world.

901
01:20:18,330 --> 01:20:23,880
Few people watch tennis on TV for the rest
of the year, but during Wimbledon, matches

902
01:20:23,880 --> 01:20:28,060
are shown on TV every afternoon and evening.

903
01:20:28,060 --> 01:20:34,160
England's most famous tennis player was Fred
Perry, who won the Wimbledon Championship

904
01:20:34,160 --> 01:20:40,040
every year for three years, from 1934 to 1936.

905
01:20:40,040 --> 01:20:47,140
Since that time, no English player has won
the Men's Championship.

906
01:20:47,140 --> 01:20:51,270
Horse-racing is another very popular sport
in England.

907
01:20:51,270 --> 01:20:57,390
There are races every day of the year, and
people enjoy making bets on which horse will

908
01:20:57,390 --> 01:20:59,290
win.

909
01:20:59,290 --> 01:21:06,630
The Derby at Epsom, which continues to be
held today, was the first derby ever, and

910
01:21:06,630 --> 01:21:14,660
derbies - races on flat ground for three-year-old
horses - are now held around the world.

911
01:21:14,660 --> 01:21:20,770
Other important dates in horseracing are the
Grand National in Liverpool in April - one

912
01:21:20,770 --> 01:21:27,790
of the most difficult horse races in the world
- and Royal Ascot, five days of horse racing

913
01:21:27,790 --> 01:21:30,210
in Berkshire in June.

914
01:21:30,210 --> 01:21:37,620
The Queen always goes to Ascot, so it is an
important event in England, and visitors wear

915
01:21:37,620 --> 01:21:41,980
their best clothes and hats.

916
01:21:41,980 --> 01:21:48,390
Another important day for sport in England
is the London Marathon in April.

917
01:21:48,390 --> 01:21:54,060
More than thirty thousand people run in the
London Marathon, which has been held since

918
01:21:54,060 --> 01:21:55,580
1981.

919
01:21:55,580 --> 01:22:03,470
The fastest people finish the forty-two kilometer
run in just over two hours, but for many runners

920
01:22:03,470 --> 01:22:08,910
the most important thing is making money for
charity.

921
01:22:08,910 --> 01:22:14,850
Watersports are popular in England, and many
people, especially on the south coast, enjoy

922
01:22:14,850 --> 01:22:16,660
sailing.

923
01:22:16,660 --> 01:22:22,140
There are good waves for surfing at many of
the beaches in the south-west, and canoeing

924
01:22:22,140 --> 01:22:27,510
is also popular on England's many rivers and
canals.

925
01:22:27,510 --> 01:22:33,881
Two of England's most famous sportspeople
do a watersport - Steve Redgrave, who won

926
01:22:33,881 --> 01:22:42,250
gold medals for rowing at every Olympic Games
between 1984 and 2000, and Ellen MacArthur,

927
01:22:42,250 --> 01:22:49,710
who broke the world record for sailing around
the world alone in the fastest time on 7th

928
01:22:49,710 --> 01:22:52,040
February 2005.

929
01:22:52,040 --> 01:22:57,970
Golf is also a very popular sport for English
people.

930
01:22:57,970 --> 01:23:04,770
There are many golf courses in England, and
every July the Open Championship, one of the

931
01:23:04,770 --> 01:23:11,390
four biggest tournaments in the world, is
held in England or Scotland.

932
01:23:11,390 --> 01:23:17,540
Motor-racing is also well-liked, and many
people go to a course called Silverstone in

933
01:23:17,540 --> 01:23:23,160
Northamptonshire every year to watch the British
Grand Prix.

934
01:23:23,160 --> 01:23:30,220
At school, children play football, rugby,
netball and cricket, and do athletics in the

935
01:23:30,220 --> 01:23:31,780
summer.

936
01:23:31,780 --> 01:23:38,690
There are public swimming pools and gyms in
most towns, and many people also enjoy cycling

937
01:23:38,690 --> 01:23:41,230
and walking.

938
01:23:41,230 --> 01:23:47,290
Other outdoor activities like mountaineering
- climbing and walking in the hills and mountains

939
01:23:47,290 --> 01:23:51,180
- are also very popular in England.

940
01:23:51,180 --> 01:23:54,190
English people love sport.

941
01:23:54,190 --> 01:23:59,290
For some time, they have not won many big
events in the sports that first came from

942
01:23:59,290 --> 01:24:02,510
their country many years before.

943
01:24:02,510 --> 01:24:13,110
But sport continues to be a very important
part of life in England.

944
01:24:13,110 --> 01:24:25,840
CHAPTER EIGHT

945
01:24:25,840 --> 01:24:32,210
Entertainment

946
01:24:32,210 --> 01:24:37,750
England is famous around the world for its
great culture and entertainment.

947
01:24:37,750 --> 01:24:43,660
Some of the worlds greatest writers, best
films, and most famous actors and directors

948
01:24:43,660 --> 01:24:50,120
have come from England, and there are several
hundred theatres and concert halls showing

949
01:24:50,120 --> 01:24:53,540
wonderful plays, music and dance.

950
01:24:53,540 --> 01:24:59,820
Literature is a very important part of England's
history, and all around the country you can

951
01:24:59,820 --> 01:25:04,670
visit the homes of some of the many great
English writers.

952
01:25:04,670 --> 01:25:11,000
The most famous of these is, of course, William
Shakespeare, but many others have written

953
01:25:11,000 --> 01:25:14,060
great works of literature too.

954
01:25:14,060 --> 01:25:20,770
In the late seventeenth century, there were
some fine poets, for example John Milton,

955
01:25:20,770 --> 01:25:24,370
who wrote Paradise Lost.

956
01:25:24,370 --> 01:25:30,070
Novels only began to be widely written in
the eighteenth century, and one of the earliest

957
01:25:30,070 --> 01:25:38,120
of these was Daniel Defoe's Robinson Crusoe,
published in 1719, which continues to be very

958
01:25:38,120 --> 01:25:40,450
popular today.

959
01:25:40,450 --> 01:25:45,320
The first half of the nineteenth century was
famous for the Romantic poetry of writers

960
01:25:45,320 --> 01:25:49,640
like Wordsworth, Coleridge, Byron, Shelley
and Keats.

961
01:25:49,640 --> 01:25:54,710
Jane Austen was another great writer of this
time.

962
01:25:54,710 --> 01:26:02,280
In books like Emma, Pride and Prejudice and
Persuasion, Austen wrote about how women saw

963
01:26:02,280 --> 01:26:06,180
society, marriage and happiness.

964
01:26:06,180 --> 01:26:13,950
Famous Victorian writers included Charles
Dickens, the Bronte sisters and George Eliot.

965
01:26:13,950 --> 01:26:20,640
In Victorian times, people began for the first
time to write literature just for children,

966
01:26:20,640 --> 01:26:26,500
and one of the best-known of these new children's
books was Lewis Carroll's Alice's Adventures

967
01:26:26,500 --> 01:26:33,210
in Wonderland, which continues to be read
by many children even today.

968
01:26:33,210 --> 01:26:39,130
Another writer from around this time whose
work is much-loved now is Arthur Conan Doyle,

969
01:26:39,130 --> 01:26:41,100
who was Scottish.

970
01:26:41,100 --> 01:26:49,170
He wrote stories about Sherlock Holmes, a
London detective, between 1880 and 1907.

971
01:26:49,170 --> 01:26:56,080
Sherlock Holmes had a brilliant mind and was
able to find the answers to the strangest

972
01:26:56,080 --> 01:26:58,060
mysteries.

973
01:26:58,060 --> 01:27:02,670
The stories of these mysteries were told to
the reader by Sherlock Holmes's great friend

974
01:27:02,670 --> 01:27:05,570
Dr Watson.

975
01:27:05,570 --> 01:27:11,330
An important English writer at the beginning
of the twentieth century was Thomas Hardy.

976
01:27:11,330 --> 01:27:17,920
Tess of the d'Urbervilles, Far From the Madding
Crowd and Hardy's other novels were often

977
01:27:17,920 --> 01:27:24,500
terribly sad stories about people in an imaginary
county called Wessex.

978
01:27:24,500 --> 01:27:32,170
Rudyard Kipling was also popular at this time
and from 1910, a new kind of 'modernist' literature

979
01:27:32,170 --> 01:27:35,000
became important.

980
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:42,480
One of the first modernist writers was Joseph
Conrad, who was Polish, but lived in England,

981
01:27:42,480 --> 01:27:48,430
and between the two wars there was a lot of
other new literature, from writers like Virginia

982
01:27:48,430 --> 01:27:53,650
Woolf, Evelyn Waugh and DH Lawrence.

983
01:27:53,650 --> 01:27:59,710
After the Second World War, two of England's
most important writers were George Orwell,

984
01:27:59,710 --> 01:28:07,090
who wrote Nineteen Eighty-Four and Animal
Farm, and Agatha Christie, who wrote sixty-six

985
01:28:07,090 --> 01:28:14,610
detective novels, including the adventures
of Miss Marple and Hercule Poirot.

986
01:28:14,610 --> 01:28:20,190
Modern fantasy literature - writing about
magic, monsters and other imaginary things

987
01:28:20,190 --> 01:28:28,090
- became popular at this time too, when The
Lord of the Rings, by JRR Tolkien, was published

988
01:28:28,090 --> 01:28:29,800
in 1949.

989
01:28:29,800 --> 01:28:36,110
Two of the most famous writers of the last
fifty years are children's writers.

990
01:28:36,110 --> 01:28:42,910
Roald Dahl, who was born in Wales to Norwegian
parents, wrote books such as Charlie and the

991
01:28:42,910 --> 01:28:50,020
Chocolate Factory and Matilda, many of which
also became great films and theatre shows.

992
01:28:50,020 --> 01:28:57,260
JK Rowling's Harry Potter series - a group
of seven fantasy books for children - has

993
01:28:57,260 --> 01:29:03,470
sold hundreds of millions of copies, and people
can now read them in sixty-seven different

994
01:29:03,470 --> 01:29:05,340
languages.

995
01:29:05,340 --> 01:29:11,340
Many of these works of literature have become
famous plays, and for many people an important

996
01:29:11,340 --> 01:29:15,320
part of any visit to England is a trip to
the theatre.

997
01:29:15,320 --> 01:29:21,530
There are several hundred theatres in England,
around the country, but the most famous are

998
01:29:21,530 --> 01:29:24,370
the theatres of the West End in London.

999
01:29:24,370 --> 01:29:31,270
In the West End, there is a theatre on nearly
every street, showing the latest plays and

1000
01:29:31,270 --> 01:29:38,960
musicals, and many of the best actors from
all around the world come to perform here.

1001
01:29:38,960 --> 01:29:45,270
Some of the most famous shows in the West
End have been musicals, such as Cats and Phantom

1002
01:29:45,270 --> 01:29:51,480
of the Opera by Andrew Lloyd Webber, but in
London and around the country, you can also

1003
01:29:51,480 --> 01:30:00,010
see many different kinds of shows, including
more serious plays, new works and comedy.

1004
01:30:00,010 --> 01:30:05,630
One of the oldest theatres in London is the
Old Vic, which first began to show plays in

1005
01:30:05,630 --> 01:30:07,470
1818.

1006
01:30:07,470 --> 01:30:14,830
England also has the National Theatre, on
London's South Bank near the London Eye, which

1007
01:30:14,830 --> 01:30:17,270
opened in 1976.

1008
01:30:17,270 --> 01:30:24,360
Across the Thames are the Royal Ballet and
the Royal Opera House at Covent Garden, and

1009
01:30:24,360 --> 01:30:30,110
the English National Opera at the Coliseum,
the largest theatre in London.

1010
01:30:30,110 --> 01:30:36,670
Outside London, England's most famous theatre
is the theatre of the Royal Shakespeare Company

1011
01:30:36,670 --> 01:30:42,530
in Stratford-upon-Avon, where Shakespeare's
plays are performed throughout the year.

1012
01:30:42,530 --> 01:30:49,890
In the summer, you can also see Shakespeare's
plays at the Globe Theatre in London, a round

1013
01:30:49,890 --> 01:30:55,610
theatre with no roof, like the one where these
famous plays were first performed more than

1014
01:30:55,610 --> 01:30:58,650
four hundred years ago.

1015
01:30:58,650 --> 01:31:01,230
England is important for its music too.

1016
01:31:01,230 --> 01:31:08,590
George Frideric Handel, Edward Elgar and Gustav
Holst are three of the country's most famous

1017
01:31:08,590 --> 01:31:15,230
classical music composers, and at places like
the Royal Festival Hall and the Barbican Centre

1018
01:31:15,230 --> 01:31:21,070
in London, you can hear many different kinds
of classical music, played by some of the

1019
01:31:21,070 --> 01:31:23,670
finest orchestras in the world.

1020
01:31:23,670 --> 01:31:30,540
There is also a lot of good classical music
outside London: the Birmingham Symphony Orchestra

1021
01:31:30,540 --> 01:31:36,990
is one of the best in Europe, and at many
stately homes and castles around the country

1022
01:31:36,990 --> 01:31:40,130
there are outdoor concerts in the summer.

1023
01:31:40,130 --> 01:31:44,840
But it is for its pop music that England is
best known.

1024
01:31:44,840 --> 01:31:51,620
Together with the USA, the UK brought rock
'n' roll to the world in the 1950s, and The

1025
01:31:51,620 --> 01:32:00,150
Beatles, who became popular in the 1960s,
is one of the most famous bands in the world.

1026
01:32:00,150 --> 01:32:07,340
During the 1960s, the Rolling Stones, Cliff
Richard and The Shadows, The Who, The Kinks,

1027
01:32:07,340 --> 01:32:14,420
The Animals and many other bands became important
in England, and they started to become famous

1028
01:32:14,420 --> 01:32:16,770
in the USA too.

1029
01:32:16,770 --> 01:32:23,140
For a while, the USA began to follow the UK
in music and in fashion.

1030
01:32:23,140 --> 01:32:27,460
In the 1970s, music changed.

1031
01:32:27,460 --> 01:32:34,010
First there was glam rock from artists like
David Bowie and Elton John, who coloured their

1032
01:32:34,010 --> 01:32:38,130
hair, and wore strange and wonderful clothes
and shoes.

1033
01:32:38,130 --> 01:32:46,160
Then came punk rock - short, fast songs, often
with a political message, sung by bands like

1034
01:32:46,160 --> 01:32:47,420
the Clash.

1035
01:32:47,420 --> 01:32:57,110
In the 1980s, world music, heavy metal (loud,
hard music) and indie rock were popular, and

1036
01:32:57,110 --> 01:33:00,460
England's dance music culture also began.

1037
01:33:00,460 --> 01:33:06,421
But in the late 1990s, some artists turned
against the many fashions in music of the

1038
01:33:06,421 --> 01:33:15,670
'80s and early '90s, and Britpop arrived - bands
such as Blur, Oasis and Radiohead that followed

1039
01:33:15,670 --> 01:33:21,050
the British guitar music of the 1960s and
'70s.

1040
01:33:21,050 --> 01:33:25,730
Several of these bands became famous around
Europe and in the USA.

1041
01:33:25,730 --> 01:33:32,290
Today, you can see bands play in clubs in
almost every big city, and there are also

1042
01:33:32,290 --> 01:33:38,400
music festivals around the country where people
camp and watch music in big fields.

1043
01:33:38,400 --> 01:33:42,710
The most famous of these is at Glastonbury.

1044
01:33:42,710 --> 01:33:46,510
Art-lovers can find a lot to enjoy in England
too.

1045
01:33:46,510 --> 01:33:52,640
Two of England's most famous artists were
the landscape painters John Constable and

1046
01:33:52,640 --> 01:34:00,780
JMW Turner, and many of their pictures can
be seen at the Tate Britain gallery in London.

1047
01:34:00,780 --> 01:34:06,850
London also has the Tate Modern, of course,
and there are also great exhibitions at the

1048
01:34:06,850 --> 01:34:12,750
Royal Academy of Arts, and a lot of Western
European art at the National Gallery in Trafalgar

1049
01:34:12,750 --> 01:34:14,530
Square.

1050
01:34:14,530 --> 01:34:22,380
In the 1990s, a group of artists called the
Young British Artists (YBAs) became very popular

1051
01:34:22,380 --> 01:34:24,630
in England.

1052
01:34:24,630 --> 01:34:33,090
One of the most famous YBAs was Damien Hirst,
who made a lot of art works with dead animals.

1053
01:34:33,090 --> 01:34:37,080
Some people love his work, and others hate
it!

1054
01:34:37,080 --> 01:34:45,120
Most towns in England have a cinema, and watching
films is a very popular activity for English

1055
01:34:45,120 --> 01:34:46,390
people.

1056
01:34:46,390 --> 01:34:52,800
England has made some of the world's greatest
films, and some of the most famous actors

1057
01:34:52,800 --> 01:34:55,260
and directors are English.

1058
01:34:55,260 --> 01:35:02,620
The film industry only really started in England
in the 1930s, when some famous films like

1059
01:35:02,620 --> 01:35:05,410
The 39 Steps were made.

1060
01:35:05,410 --> 01:35:12,390
But it was in the 1950s and 1960s that British
cinema became really important.

1061
01:35:12,390 --> 01:35:18,429
At this time, Hammer Horror films like The
Curse of Frankenstein and Dracula were made

1062
01:35:18,429 --> 01:35:25,090
- and Ealing Comedies like Kind Hearts and
Coronets and Whisky Galore.

1063
01:35:25,090 --> 01:35:31,420
The first Carry On film was made in 1958,
and by 1992, there were thirty-one.

1064
01:35:31,420 --> 01:35:39,130
The Carry On films were comedies that made
jokes about English life.

1065
01:35:39,130 --> 01:35:45,190
They were not thought of as important films,
but were loved by many English people.

1066
01:35:45,190 --> 01:35:50,520
The James Bond films were another series that
became very famous in England.

1067
01:35:50,520 --> 01:35:57,100
The stories were adventures about James Bond,
a secret service agent - someone who worked

1068
01:35:57,100 --> 01:36:02,380
secretly for the government, looking for enemies
of the country.

1069
01:36:02,380 --> 01:36:10,000
The first Bond film, Dr No, was made in 1962,
and the films became famous for their music,

1070
01:36:10,000 --> 01:36:16,550
Bond's cars and clever equipment, and for
James Bond himself - a character played by

1071
01:36:16,550 --> 01:36:18,750
several different actors.

1072
01:36:18,750 --> 01:36:26,690
A famous English actor of the 1960s was Julie
Andrews, who appeared in two famous musical

1073
01:36:26,690 --> 01:36:30,750
films, The Sound of Music and Mary Poppins.

1074
01:36:30,750 --> 01:36:35,810
But many people believe that the greatest
actor of the twentieth century was Laurence

1075
01:36:35,810 --> 01:36:37,330
Olivier.

1076
01:36:37,330 --> 01:36:45,640
Olivier, who worked in theatre and film from
the 1920s until the 1980s, made nearly sixty

1077
01:36:45,640 --> 01:36:50,300
films, including Rebecca and Wuthering Heights.

1078
01:36:50,300 --> 01:36:56,920
Also very famous, but as a director not an
actor, was Alfred Hitchcock.

1079
01:36:56,920 --> 01:37:04,440
He made many great mystery films in England
and in Hollywood, where he later went to live.

1080
01:37:04,440 --> 01:37:10,550
From the 1990s, romantic comedies like Four
Weddings and a Funeral and Notting Hill were

1081
01:37:10,550 --> 01:37:17,710
made, and the Merchant Ivory films of classic
novels like Howard's End.

1082
01:37:17,710 --> 01:37:25,030
Since then, some of England's most successful
films have been Love Actually, Slumdog Millionaire

1083
01:37:25,030 --> 01:37:27,630
and the Harry Potter series.

1084
01:37:27,630 --> 01:37:34,030
But England's most popular kind of entertainment
is television.

1085
01:37:34,030 --> 01:37:41,090
Public television first began in England in
1936, and the British Broadcasting Corporation

1086
01:37:41,090 --> 01:37:49,710
(the BBC) is the world's oldest and largest
broadcaster Today there are five main channels

1087
01:37:49,710 --> 01:37:56,530
in England, and there are also hundreds more
channels on cable and satellite TV.

1088
01:37:56,530 --> 01:37:59,330
There are hundreds of radio stations too.

1089
01:37:59,330 --> 01:38:05,670
On English TV, there are many different kinds
of programmers, but some of the most popular

1090
01:38:05,670 --> 01:38:14,370
ones are sitcoms (situation comedies) - comedies
about people in their home or where they work.

1091
01:38:14,370 --> 01:38:20,920
One of the most famous of these was Fawlty
Towers, with the actor John Cleese.

1092
01:38:20,920 --> 01:38:27,650
Many people also enjoy soap operas - dramas
which continue from one programme to the next,

1093
01:38:27,650 --> 01:38:34,630
for example Eastenders, Coronation Street,
Emmerdale and Hollyoaks.

1094
01:38:34,630 --> 01:38:41,490
Another very popular drama series in England
in the 1990s was Inspector Morse, about a

1095
01:38:41,490 --> 01:38:43,360
detective in Oxford.

1096
01:38:43,360 --> 01:38:52,090
Many people also enjoy reality programmes
- programmes about ordinary people's lives.

1097
01:38:52,090 --> 01:38:57,880
One of the most famous of these is Big Brother,
a programme in which a group of people live

1098
01:38:57,880 --> 01:39:02,930
together in a house and are filmed twenty-four
hours a day.

1099
01:39:02,930 --> 01:39:08,130
Some of the Big Brother programmes have been
watched by up to six million people in the

1100
01:39:08,130 --> 01:39:16,800
UK: England has great music, art, history
and literature, but sometimes people are most

1101
01:39:16,800 --> 01:39:29,700
interested in day-to-day life!

1102
01:39:29,700 --> 01:39:41,590
CHAPTER NINE

1103
01:39:41,590 --> 01:39:44,840
English Heroes

1104
01:39:44,840 --> 01:39:51,620
Who are England's heroes - the important people
who will never be forgotten?

1105
01:39:51,620 --> 01:39:58,980
One of the greatest must be William Shakespeare,
who wrote many beautiful poems and about thirty-seven

1106
01:39:58,980 --> 01:40:06,080
plays, including A Midsummer Night's Dream,
Romeo and Juliet, Hamlet and Macbeth.

1107
01:40:06,080 --> 01:40:13,270
The people in his plays always seem very real,
and he wrote about their feelings and problems

1108
01:40:13,270 --> 01:40:19,900
in words that continue to sound new and interesting
today.

1109
01:40:19,900 --> 01:40:25,710
Another hero of England from the world of
literature is Charles Dickens.

1110
01:40:25,710 --> 01:40:32,860
Dickens wrote some of the best novels of Victorian
times, including Oliver Twist, David Copperfield,

1111
01:40:32,860 --> 01:40:35,820
Bleak House and Little Dorrit.

1112
01:40:35,820 --> 01:40:41,720
Dickens used his books to show how terrible
life was for poor people in England at the

1113
01:40:41,720 --> 01:40:44,250
time of the industrial revolution.

1114
01:40:44,250 --> 01:40:51,340
But England has scientific heroes as well
as heroes from the world of literature.

1115
01:40:51,340 --> 01:40:55,090
One of the greatest of these was Sir Isaac
Newton.

1116
01:40:55,090 --> 01:41:03,290
Born in Lincolnshire in 1643, Newton studied
at the University of Cambridge.

1117
01:41:03,290 --> 01:41:08,480
He was able to understand and explain many
things about the world around us for the first

1118
01:41:08,480 --> 01:41:15,390
time, and his book Mathematical Principles
of Natural Philosophy was very important in

1119
01:41:15,390 --> 01:41:17,910
the history of science.

1120
01:41:17,910 --> 01:41:23,840
Newton helped people to understand about light
and colour, and he was also the first person

1121
01:41:23,840 --> 01:41:29,410
to explain gravity - the force that pulls
things towards the ground.

1122
01:41:29,410 --> 01:41:34,410
Charles Darwin also did scientific work in
England.

1123
01:41:34,410 --> 01:41:42,770
He was born into a rich family, and in 1831
he left England to travel around the world.

1124
01:41:42,770 --> 01:41:48,410
Darwin studied the animals and plants that
he saw on his trip, and was interested in

1125
01:41:48,410 --> 01:41:51,320
the differences between them.

1126
01:41:51,320 --> 01:41:58,490
When he came home, he began to work on a new
idea: the theory of evolution.

1127
01:41:58,490 --> 01:42:04,800
This was the idea that only the strongest
animals and plants lived and reproduced - had

1128
01:42:04,800 --> 01:42:07,780
babies or grew seeds.

1129
01:42:07,780 --> 01:42:15,250
And so, Darwin believed, each kind of animal
and plant was slowly changing.

1130
01:42:15,250 --> 01:42:23,490
In 1859, Darwin published his ideas in the
book On the Origin of Species.

1131
01:42:23,490 --> 01:42:31,540
One very real hero of England was Horatio
Nelson, who was leader of the Royal Navy from

1132
01:42:31,540 --> 01:42:35,020
1794 to 1805.

1133
01:42:35,020 --> 01:42:42,501
Nelson, who lost one eye and one arm in battle,
was a great leader, and with him, Britain

1134
01:42:42,501 --> 01:42:47,140
won many battles against France during the
Napoleonic Wars.

1135
01:42:47,140 --> 01:42:53,770
At the Battle of Trafalgar, Nelson helped
to stop the French from invading Britain,

1136
01:42:53,770 --> 01:42:56,090
but he was then killed.

1137
01:42:56,090 --> 01:43:02,840
A very large statue of him stands forty-six
meters high in Trafalgar Square and is one

1138
01:43:02,840 --> 01:43:05,370
of London's best-loved sights.

1139
01:43:05,370 --> 01:43:12,490
Two other important English seamen were Sir
Francis Drake and Captain Cook.

1140
01:43:12,490 --> 01:43:20,150
Sir Francis Drake helped to lead England against
the Spanish Armada in 1588, and Captain Cook

1141
01:43:20,150 --> 01:43:27,460
was the first European to reach the east coast
of Australia, in 1770.

1142
01:43:27,460 --> 01:43:35,330
Winston Churchill, prime minister from 1940
until 1945, was another English hero for many

1143
01:43:35,330 --> 01:43:38,700
people during World War Two.

1144
01:43:38,700 --> 01:43:44,650
Churchill was a strong leader, and many people
believe that the speeches and radio broadcasts

1145
01:43:44,650 --> 01:43:50,530
he made during the war helped the UK to win
the war.

1146
01:43:50,530 --> 01:43:59,570
He was prime minister again from 1951 to 1955,
and when he died in 1965, the Queen gave him

1147
01:43:59,570 --> 01:44:07,340
a state funeral - a special funeral that is
normally only for kings and queens.

1148
01:44:07,340 --> 01:44:10,920
Another famous politician was Margaret Thatcher.

1149
01:44:10,920 --> 01:44:18,880
Thatcher was prime minister from 1979 to 1990
- longer than any other person in the twentieth

1150
01:44:18,880 --> 01:44:25,820
century - and she was also the first woman
prime minister of the UK.

1151
01:44:25,820 --> 01:44:30,940
One of England's most famous heroes is not
actually real.

1152
01:44:30,940 --> 01:44:36,670
Stories about Robin Hood have been popular
since the Middle Ages, and in modern times

1153
01:44:36,670 --> 01:44:41,930
many films, plays and TV programmes have been
made about him.

1154
01:44:41,930 --> 01:44:49,060
In these old stories, Robin Hood is a great
fighter and an outlaw - someone who does not

1155
01:44:49,060 --> 01:44:51,150
follow the law.

1156
01:44:51,150 --> 01:44:57,400
Living in Sherwood Forest at a time when the
king of England is a dishonest man, he takes

1157
01:44:57,400 --> 01:45:01,800
money from the rich to give it to the poor.

1158
01:45:01,800 --> 01:45:08,670
Florence Nightingale was famous for helping
people too - but she was a real person.

1159
01:45:08,670 --> 01:45:14,550
Florence Nightingale is thought of by many
as the first real nurse.

1160
01:45:14,550 --> 01:45:21,600
In 1854, during the Crimean War, she went
to work in a hospital for soldiers.

1161
01:45:21,600 --> 01:45:30,080
She thought that it was dirty and badly organized,
so she quickly started to make important changes.

1162
01:45:30,080 --> 01:45:35,820
Because of her, the hospital became cleaner,
the soldiers were given good food and taken

1163
01:45:35,820 --> 01:45:40,640
care of better, and soon fewer people were
dying.

1164
01:45:40,640 --> 01:45:46,400
When she came back to England, Florence Nightingale
started the first proper nursing school at

1165
01:45:46,400 --> 01:45:49,610
St Thomas' Hospital.

1166
01:45:49,610 --> 01:45:53,750
England also has heroes of the stage and screen.

1167
01:45:53,750 --> 01:45:59,770
One of the first of these was Charlie Chaplin,
a comedy actor and director who was famous

1168
01:45:59,770 --> 01:46:06,240
for his many silent films in the years before
films with sound were made.

1169
01:46:06,240 --> 01:46:12,510
Chaplin's best-known character was 'The Tramp',
a funny little man with a hat, a moustache

1170
01:46:12,510 --> 01:46:14,110
and a stick.

1171
01:46:14,110 --> 01:46:21,420
Before the end of the First World War, Chaplin
was the most famous film actor in the world.

1172
01:46:21,420 --> 01:46:26,680
But probably the greatest stage heroes of
England are The Beatles.

1173
01:46:26,680 --> 01:46:35,091
John Lennon, Paul McCartney, George Harrison
and Ringo Starr had their first hit, Love

1174
01:46:35,091 --> 01:46:44,420
Me Do, in 1962, and by 1964, they had become
famous around the world.

1175
01:46:44,420 --> 01:46:50,900
There was international 'Beatlemania: people
screamed and shouted when the band came on

1176
01:46:50,900 --> 01:46:55,120
stage, and the world watched everything they
did.

1177
01:46:55,120 --> 01:47:00,780
The Beatles were the first English band to
become successful in the USA.

1178
01:47:00,780 --> 01:47:08,400
They made more than two hundred songs and
are the best-selling band in history.

1179
01:47:08,400 --> 01:47:15,940
Two more musical heroes of England, famous
in a quieter way, are the composers George

1180
01:47:15,940 --> 01:47:20,710
Frideric Handel and Sir Edward Elgar.

1181
01:47:20,710 --> 01:47:30,360
Handel was German, but came to live in London
in 1712 and became British in 1727.

1182
01:47:30,360 --> 01:47:36,390
He is one of the greatest composers in history
and is best known for wonderful works like

1183
01:47:36,390 --> 01:47:41,640
Water Music and The Messiah, written in 1742.

1184
01:47:41,640 --> 01:47:51,880
Elgar's most famous works are the Enigma Variations,
written in 1899, The Dream of Gerontius and

1185
01:47:51,880 --> 01:47:55,670
the Pomp and Circumstance Marches.

1186
01:47:55,670 --> 01:47:59,170
What about modern-day English heroes?

1187
01:47:59,170 --> 01:48:03,320
For many football lovers, David Beckham is
a hero.

1188
01:48:03,320 --> 01:48:11,080
He was captain of the England football team
from 2000 until 2006 and, along with his wife

1189
01:48:11,080 --> 01:48:19,130
Victoria, who was once in the band the Spice
Girls, Beckham is a very famous celebrity.

1190
01:48:19,130 --> 01:48:24,010
Princess Diana is also, for many people, an
English hero.

1191
01:48:24,010 --> 01:48:31,860
Diana was the first wife of Charles, the Prince
of Wales, and when they married in 1981, people

1192
01:48:31,860 --> 01:48:35,040
believed that she would one day be the queen.

1193
01:48:35,040 --> 01:48:42,380
But they were not happy together, and in 1996
Charles and Diana ended their marriage.

1194
01:48:42,380 --> 01:48:48,200
A year later, Diana was killed in a car accident
in Paris.

1195
01:48:48,200 --> 01:48:55,130
Many people loved her for her work with international
charities and because she showed great kindness

1196
01:48:55,130 --> 01:49:00,030
to children, ill people and those with difficult
lives.

1197
01:49:00,030 --> 01:49:05,740
When she died, thousands of people brought
flowers to her London home, and two-and-a-half

1198
01:49:05,740 --> 01:49:19,260
billion people watched her funeral on TV.

1199
01:49:19,260 --> 01:49:31,490
CHAPTER TEN

1200
01:49:31,490 --> 01:49:32,570
Looking Forward

1201
01:49:32,570 --> 01:49:40,970
All through England's history, small inventions
- new things that people make - have brought

1202
01:49:40,970 --> 01:49:44,340
big changes to peoples lives.

1203
01:49:44,340 --> 01:49:50,970
When William Caxton made the first English
printing press in 1476, the country changed

1204
01:49:50,970 --> 01:49:52,570
in many ways.

1205
01:49:52,570 --> 01:49:59,270
Now people could get more books, more cheaply,
and so they could get information about lots

1206
01:49:59,270 --> 01:50:01,640
of different things.

1207
01:50:01,640 --> 01:50:08,100
Because of this, information also became more
standardized: it was written down in the same

1208
01:50:08,100 --> 01:50:13,040
way each time, which was important in areas
like science.

1209
01:50:13,040 --> 01:50:17,210
The printing press changed the English language
too.

1210
01:50:17,210 --> 01:50:23,080
At that time, people in different parts of
the country used very different words, but

1211
01:50:23,080 --> 01:50:28,500
William Caxton only printed books in standardized
English.

1212
01:50:28,500 --> 01:50:36,330
The spinning Jenny, invented in 1764 by James
Hargreaves, brought more important changes

1213
01:50:36,330 --> 01:50:38,590
to England.

1214
01:50:38,590 --> 01:50:43,610
With the spinning Jenny, people working in
their homes in England could spin cotton more

1215
01:50:43,610 --> 01:50:47,780
quickly and so make much more.

1216
01:50:47,780 --> 01:50:53,650
Other machines followed, and when steam power
was introduced, cloth making became a proper

1217
01:50:53,650 --> 01:50:55,040
industry.

1218
01:50:55,040 --> 01:51:01,510
Cloth-makers did not work at home anymore;
they used big machines in factories in the

1219
01:51:01,510 --> 01:51:03,260
cities.

1220
01:51:03,260 --> 01:51:09,580
This was the beginning of the industrial revolution,
and in twenty- first century England, people

1221
01:51:09,580 --> 01:51:15,740
are in the middle of another revolution, or
great change, again started by several small

1222
01:51:15,740 --> 01:51:17,900
inventions.

1223
01:51:17,900 --> 01:51:22,760
One of the most important of these was the
invention by the Englishman Tim Berners-Lee,

1224
01:51:22,760 --> 01:51:27,840
in 1990, of the World Wide Web.

1225
01:51:27,840 --> 01:51:34,000
The World Wide Web has made it easier than
ever for people to get information.

1226
01:51:34,000 --> 01:51:41,240
Its invention is part of the digital revolution,
which has given us mobile phones, computers,

1227
01:51:41,240 --> 01:51:47,280
MP3 players, digital TV and much, much more.

1228
01:51:47,280 --> 01:51:52,490
The digital revolution is changing many things
about life in England.

1229
01:51:52,490 --> 01:51:59,140
We can now talk on the telephone almost anywhere,
send messages quickly around the world and

1230
01:51:59,140 --> 01:52:03,530
see people who are thousands of kilometers
away through our computers.

1231
01:52:03,530 --> 01:52:10,300
Because of this, people can study or work
from home more easily, and work with people

1232
01:52:10,300 --> 01:52:12,470
in different countries.

1233
01:52:12,470 --> 01:52:18,410
We can shop and meet people on the Internet,
read books on our computers and watch hundreds

1234
01:52:18,410 --> 01:52:21,370
of different TV channels.

1235
01:52:21,370 --> 01:52:27,160
And the machines we use every day, like radios,
washing machines and cameras, are becoming

1236
01:52:27,160 --> 01:52:29,670
better and cheaper all the time.

1237
01:52:29,670 --> 01:52:34,140
But the digital revolution is also bringing
new problems.

1238
01:52:34,140 --> 01:52:41,010
Many people feel that modern technology makes
life busier and sometimes more difficult.

1239
01:52:41,010 --> 01:52:49,150
We can work wherever we are now, so for some
people there is less time to think or to relax.

1240
01:52:49,150 --> 01:52:54,870
Is it good for children to play computer games
and watch TV so much?

1241
01:52:54,870 --> 01:53:00,040
And are we forgetting how to meet people and
make real friends because we talk to people

1242
01:53:00,040 --> 01:53:03,170
through computers so much now?

1243
01:53:03,170 --> 01:53:08,420
These are all difficult questions for England's
future, and there are other questions we are

1244
01:53:08,420 --> 01:53:11,290
trying to answer now too.

1245
01:53:11,290 --> 01:53:17,240
For a long time, we have known that there
are big environmental problems in the world.

1246
01:53:17,240 --> 01:53:25,110
Factories, cars, and burning coal, oil or
gas for fuel all make our air dirty, giving

1247
01:53:25,110 --> 01:53:27,410
us global warming.

1248
01:53:27,410 --> 01:53:32,170
So now we need to find ways to help the environment.

1249
01:53:32,170 --> 01:53:38,130
Many English homes and companies are already
getting their electricity from solar (sun)

1250
01:53:38,130 --> 01:53:44,460
or wind power, and the government is giving
money to people who use these renewable energies

1251
01:53:44,460 --> 01:53:48,400
- ones that can be used again and again.

1252
01:53:48,400 --> 01:53:55,960
In the future, we will probably use less and
less coal, oil and gas.

1253
01:53:55,960 --> 01:54:04,150
Many English people have been recycling more
and more of their rubbish, and by 2011, they

1254
01:54:04,150 --> 01:54:06,990
were recycling forty percent of their rubbish.

1255
01:54:06,990 --> 01:54:14,630
In the future, many people also believe that
we will use electric cars more and other energy-saving

1256
01:54:14,630 --> 01:54:16,500
technologies.

1257
01:54:16,500 --> 01:54:20,370
The digital and environmental revolutions
are changing England.

1258
01:54:20,370 --> 01:54:28,900
England in 2100 will be a very different place
to the England we now know.

1259
01:54:28,900 --> 01:54:31,840
Will England have a king or queen?

1260
01:54:31,840 --> 01:54:36,520
Will there continue to be big differences
between rich and poor people?

1261
01:54:36,520 --> 01:54:39,900
How many different languages will people speak?

1262
01:54:39,900 --> 01:54:43,370
And will England have won the Football World
Cup again?

1263
01:54:43,370 --> 01:54:45,550
We cannot know.

1264
01:54:45,550 --> 01:54:50,970
But we can probably hope that people will
continue to watch Shakespeare's plays, climb

1265
01:54:50,970 --> 01:54:55,740
the mountains of the Lake District and visit
the sights of London.

1266
01:54:55,740 --> 01:55:01,460
And perhaps they will still say that England
is a wonderful, exciting place.

